larly those which the weight of evidence tends to assign to Bracton. The omission of this passage in MC, therefore, argues against its authenticity. In the form in which it is given in V, this sentence is, in a way, half contra- dictory to what has immediately preceded it. Bracton is giving a list of those kinds of persons who are not ableto make a donation. A deaf man, qni manno non ondit, can not; but a person who is only hard of hearing may. A dumb person, qni omnino loqui non potest, may (aeneadum quosdam), for he is able to give his assent by signs and a nod. Then comes the addicto, Et generaliter tenendam est qnod nutus devectionem faeere non potest, qnia dena· ttoni ementire non potest, etc. But some of the manuscripts give a reading

Ἰ which supplements instead of opposes what has preceded-Et generaliter

tenendum est qnod nnllna donationem sonere poten qni dmenticni coenentirc non possit, etc. In this form the passage takes on the appearance of an aster- thought by Bracton. Whether or not it is we can not ‘with certainty say. Again the best way out of the difficulty is to retain the passage in the treatise while pointing out its doubthd authorship.
